Meningitis: Inflammation of the tissues surrounding the brain and spinal cord, potentially caused by infection, trauma, or autoimmune disorders.
Stroke: Blood supply interruption to the brain, leading to neurological deficits, potentially caused by a clot or burst blood vessel.
Migraine with Aura: Type of recurrent headache accompanied by sensory disturbances like aphasia or visual disturbances (aura), often throbbing or pulsating in nature.
Encephalitis: Inflammation of the brain tissue, potentially caused by infection, autoimmune disorders, or exposure to toxins.
Brain Tumor: Abnormal growth of cells within the brain, causing a range of neurological symptoms depending on location and type.
Intracranial Hemorrhage: Bleeding within the skull, potentially caused by trauma, aneurysm rupture, or other underlying conditions.
Subarachnoid Hemorrhage: Bleeding in the space between the brain and its covering, often caused by a ruptured aneurysm.
Sinus Infection: Inflammation or infection of the sinus cavities, leading to headache, facial pressure, and nasal discharge.
Cervical Spondylosis: Degenerative changes in the bones and joints of the neck, potentially causing neck pain, headache, and neurological symptoms if nerves are affected.
Lyme Disease: Tick-borne bacterial infection, potentially causing a range of symptoms including neurological involvement like headache and weakness.

description: A neurological disorder characterized by severe headaches, often accompanied by visual disturbances, known as aura. The aura typically includes symptoms such as scotoma, photophobia, and parasthesia. Weakness can also occur in some cases.
